    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on an E-7 visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, but you must notify Immigration within 15 days and apply for a status update with your new employer's documents. The new job must still be in an eligible E-7 occupation. You cannot work for the new employer until the change is approved.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Korean language required for the visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">No, Korean proficiency is not a visa requirement. However, TOPIK certification adds points for F-2-7 residency applications and is highly valued by employers. Learning Korean also dramatically improves daily life and career prospects.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get my pension contributions back when I leave?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, if you're from a country with a pension agreement with Korea (most Western countries), you can claim a lump-sum refund of your National Pension contributions when permanently leaving. Apply at the National Pension Service with your departure documents.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">The F-2-7 points-based residency requires 80+ points (from salary, education, age, Korean ability, etc.) after working legally. F-5 permanent residence typically requires 5+ years of legal residence, stable income, and basic Korean ability (KIIP or TOPIK).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse work on a dependent visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">F-3 dependent visa holders can apply for work permission but need separate authorization from Immigration for each job. It's not automatic like some countries. The process takes 2-4 weeks and requires employer sponsorship documentation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I need specialist care—do I need a referral?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">No referral needed in Korea. You can visit any specialist or hospital directly. However, visiting a clinic first and getting a referral letter can reduce your hospital copay. Major procedures may require appointments, but many specialists accept walk-ins.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        South Korea offers an excellent combination of career opportunities, affordable universal healthcare, and modern infrastructure. The E-7 visa system is straightforward for those with relevant qualifications, and large Korean companies provide strong benefits packages. NHIS coverage means healthcare costs are minimal—often shockingly low compared to Western countries.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The main challenges are work culture (long hours are common), language barriers (Korean proficiency significantly improves life quality), and the strict degree-job matching requirement. If your degree doesn't align with your target role, visa approval becomes difficult.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        For healthcare, NHIS provides excellent value. Most expats find the 20-40% copay manageable, but adding Korean private insurance (실손보험) for around ₩50,000-100,000/month covers nearly all out-of-pocket costs. International insurance is only necessary if you need global coverage or strong English support.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Bottom Line</h3>
        <p class="text-primary-800">South Korea is ideal for professionals in tech, engineering, and education who want excellent healthcare, modern city living, and exposure to Korean culture. NHIS provides outstanding value—add private insurance only for copay coverage. Learn some Korean to maximize your experience, and ensure your degree aligns with your job field for visa success.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

